**Sec. 70501**
This section amends Section 25E(g) to terminate the previously-owned clean vehicle credit by changing the eligibility deadline from December 31, 2032, to September 30, 2025. Consequently, taxpayers can no longer claim this credit for vehicles placed in service after September 30, 2025. This change effectively ends the subsidy for used electric and fuel cell vehicles earlier than previously scheduled.

**Sec. 70502**
This section amends Section 30D(h) to terminate the clean vehicle credit for new electric vehicles acquired after September 30, 2025, rather than the original December 31, 2032 deadline. It also removes specific clauses from Section 30D(e) regarding battery component sourcing and critical mineral requirements, effectively simplifying the credit's eligibility criteria before its expiration. This action eliminates the credit for new vehicles purchased after the September 2025 cutoff.

**Sec. 70503**
This section amends Section 45W(g) to terminate the qualified commercial clean vehicles credit for vehicles placed in service after September 30, 2025. Previously, this credit was available for commercial vehicles through December 31, 2032. The amendment ensures that no new commercial clean vehicle credits can be claimed after the September 2025 deadline.

**Sec. 70504**
This section amends Section 30C(i) to terminate the alternative fuel vehicle refueling property credit for property placed in service after June 30, 2026. The original expiration date for this credit was December 31, 2032. This change shortens the availability of the credit for charging stations and fueling infrastructure by approximately six years.

**Sec. 70505**
This section amends Section 25C(h) to terminate the energy efficient home improvement credit for property placed in service after December 31, 2025. It also modifies the definition of eligible oil furnaces and hot water boilers to require them to meet 2021 Energy Star criteria and be rated for fuel blends containing at least 20 percent eligible fuel. This effectively ends the credit for most home efficiency upgrades after the end of 2025.

**Sec. 70506**
This section amends Section 25D(h) to terminate the residential clean energy credit for expenditures made after December 31, 2025. It also removes the provision that would have reduced the credit percentage from 30 percent to 26 percent in 2033 and 22 percent in 2034. Consequently, the credit remains at 30 percent for eligible expenditures made through the end of 2025 before expiring.

**Sec. 70507**
This section amends Section 179D to terminate the energy efficient commercial buildings deduction for property where construction begins after June 30, 2026. Previously, this deduction was available for construction beginning through December 31, 2032. This change limits the deduction for commercial building efficiency improvements to projects starting before mid-2026.

**Sec. 70508**
This section amends Section 45L(h) to terminate the new energy efficient home credit for homes placed in service after June 30, 2026. The original expiration date for this credit was December 31, 2032. This amendment reduces the availability of the credit for builders of new energy-efficient homes by approximately six years.

**Sec. 70509**
This section amends Section 168(e)(3)(B)(vi) to remove the special depreciation allowance for energy property, effectively terminating the bonus depreciation for such assets. The amendment applies to property where construction begins after December 31, 2024. This change eliminates the immediate expensing benefit for energy property investments starting in 2025.

**Sec. 70510**
This section amends Section 45U(c) to prohibit the zero-emission nuclear power production credit for taxpayers that are specified foreign entities immediately upon enactment. It further prohibits the credit for foreign-influenced entities for taxable years beginning two years after the date of enactment. These restrictions target foreign control over nuclear power production facilities receiving federal tax credits.

**Sec. 70511**
This section amends Section 45V(c)(3)(C) to terminate the clean hydrogen production credit for hydrogen produced after January 1, 2028. The original expiration date for this credit was January 1, 2033. This change shortens the duration of the subsidy for clean hydrogen production by five years.

**Sec. 70512**
This section amends Section 45Y to terminate the clean electricity production credit for wind and solar facilities placed in service after December 31, 2027. It also imposes strict restrictions prohibiting credits for facilities involving material assistance from prohibited foreign entities or owned by specified foreign entities. The section defines "prohibited foreign entities" to include Chinese military companies and entities controlled by covered nations, with specific thresholds for material assistance costs.

**Sec. 70513**
This section amends Section 48E to terminate the clean electricity investment credit for wind and solar facilities placed in service after December 31, 2027. It similarly restricts credits for facilities involving material assistance from prohibited foreign entities and prohibits transfers of credits to specified foreign entities. The section also modifies domestic content requirements, increasing the percentage of domestic content needed for qualified investments starting in 2026.

**Sec. 70514**
This section amends Section 45X to phase out the advanced manufacturing production credit for applicable critical minerals, reducing the credit amount by 25 percent annually from 2031 to 2033 before terminating it. It also terminates the credit for wind energy components produced after December 31, 2027, and metallurgical coal produced after December 31, 2029. Additionally, it adds restrictions prohibiting credits for components involving material assistance from prohibited foreign entities.

**Sec. 70515**
This section amends Section 48C(e)(3)(C) to prevent the increase of the advanced energy project credit program's allocation limits. The amendment ensures that the total amount of credits available under the program does not increase beyond current statutory limits. This change effectively freezes the funding cap for the advanced energy project credit program.

**Sec. 70521**
This section amends Section 45Z to extend the clean fuel production credit through December 31, 2029, and restricts eligible feedstocks to those produced in the United States, Mexico, or Canada. It prohibits negative emission rates for transportation fuels, except for those derived from animal manure. The section also coordinates credits to prevent double benefits for sustainable aviation fuel and extends the small agri-biodiesel producer credit.

**Sec. 70522**
This section amends Section 45Q to prohibit the carbon oxide sequestration credit for taxpayers that are specified foreign entities or foreign-influenced entities. It also equalizes the credit amounts for different uses of qualified carbon oxide, setting the credit at $17 per metric ton (adjusted for inflation) for secure geological storage. The amendment ensures parity between credits for storage and those for enhanced oil recovery.

**Sec. 70523**
This section amends Section 56A(c)(13) to modify the calculation of adjusted financial statement income for the alternative minimum tax. It allows taxpayers to reduce adjusted financial statement income by depreciation deductions and intangible drilling and development costs that were deducted for regular tax purposes. This change applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70524**
This section amends Section 7704(d)(1)(E) to expand the definition of qualifying income for publicly traded partnerships. It includes income from the transportation or storage of hydrogen, carbon capture, advanced nuclear, hydropower, and geothermal energy. This change allows these specific energy sectors to maintain their partnership tax status without being taxed as corporations.

**Sec. 70525**
This section adds Section 6435 to the Internal Revenue Code to allow payments to individuals who remove eligible indelibly dyed diesel fuel or kerosene from a terminal. The payment amount equals the tax previously paid on the fuel, which is exempt from taxation under Section 4082(a). This provision applies to fuel removed on or after 180 days following the enactment of the Act.

**Sec. 70531**
This section amends the Tariff Act of 1930 to impose civil penalties of up to $5,000 for the first violation and $10,000 for subsequent violations for using the de minimis entry privilege for commercial shipments that violate customs laws. It also repeals the commercial shipment exception for de minimis entries, which previously allowed small shipments to enter duty-free. These changes take effect 30 days after enactment and July 1, 2027, respectively.

**Sec. 70601**
This section amends Section 461(l) to make the limitation on excess business losses of noncorporate taxpayers permanent, removing the original expiration date of December 31, 2028. It also adjusts the inflation indexing for the limitation amount to use 2025 and 2024 as the base years instead of 2018 and 2017. This change ensures the limitation applies indefinitely to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2026.

**Sec. 70602**
This section amends Section 707(a)(2) to clarify that payments from a partnership to a partner for property or services are generally treated as guaranteed payments rather than distributions. The amendment removes the phrase "Under regulations prescribed" to establish a statutory rule for this treatment. This change applies to services performed and property transferred after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70603**
This section amends Section 162(m) to apply the $1,000,000 compensation deduction limit to all members of a controlled group of corporations for specified covered employees. It requires the deduction limit to be allocated among the controlled group members based on the ratio of remuneration provided by each member. This change applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70604**
This section adds Subchapter C to Chapter 36 to impose a 1 percent excise tax on remittance transfers made using cash, money orders, or cashier's checks. The tax is collected by the remittance transfer provider from the sender and remitted quarterly to the Secretary. The tax does not apply to transfers funded by debit or credit cards or withdrawals from regulated financial institutions. This provision applies to transfers made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70605**
This section imposes a $1,000 penalty on promoters who fail to comply with due diligence requirements regarding the COVID-related Employee Retention Tax Credit (ERTC). It defines a "COVID-ERTC promoter" based on the percentage of gross receipts derived from such services and limits the ability to claim refunds for credits filed after January 31, 2024. The section also extends the statute of limitations for assessing taxes related to improperly claimed ERTC wages to six years.

**Sec. 70606**
This section amends Section 25A to require taxpayers to include their social security number and the social security number of the student to claim the American Opportunity and Lifetime Learning credits. It also mandates the inclusion of the educational institution's employer identification number on the tax return. This requirement applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70607**
This section appropriates $15,000,000 to the Department of the Treasury to fund a task force that must report to Congress within 90 days on replacing the IRS Direct File program. The report must analyze the costs and feasibility of public-private partnerships for free tax filing and taxpayer preferences for government-run versus private sector services. The funds are available until September 30, 2026. [end of text]


